column168: Flight 2285/FLL PAP departed at approximately 1415 from FLL out of gate F8. The aircraft was took off at 1438 then returned gate F8 at approximately 1450. The captain called into to operations and declared an emergency. The aircraft was parked at gate F8 and all passengers were deplaned safely with no issues in less 15min. All passengers were asked to leave there carry-on bags. The captain came off the aircraft and explained that they smelled something in the cockpit/cabin right after takeoff that smelled like fuel and or finger nail polish. So he turned the aircraft around as soon as possible.     The aircraft was deplaned and the fire department/police arrived on scene. The fire department contacted the Airport Fire Rescue Environmental department.Fire Rescue explained that they will go onboard the aircraft with a device that alarms if there is any explosives/combustibles odors. They cleared the passenger cabin first and then check the cargo bins of the aircraft. The team went on board the aircraft at 1530 in the passenger cabin. At approximately 1545 Fire Rescue reported that there was no activity from the machine to report from the passenger cabin. At 1550 they checked the forward cargo compartment for signs of gases, nothing was found. At 1558 Fire Rescue opened the rear cargo door and there machines had a hint on a smell, coming from the rear cargo compartment.    It was at this point Fire Rescue advised us to unload the rear of aircraft 3EA to search for the bag. At approximately 1630 a bag was found triggered the device with high levels of flammable gas near or around a brown bag.    The bag was tag number 726430, checked in under passenger Isaac/Melinda Rose, PNR KCUTNU  this bag was opened to reveal over 30 different toiletries in the bag. On the top of the bag it was found that 1 aerosol can of Finesse hair spray had been disbursed approximately 300ml. 1 bottle of hydrogen peroxide appeered to have leaked 450ml and also a bottle of Bath and Body hand soap approximately 8 oz leaked. After all was found the Fire Rescue cleared the scene.    All these items had leaked and fumigated inside the passengers bag. All passengers were given meal vouchers while they waited for Fire  Rescue to clear the scene, the passengers were rebooked for a future flight and many received hotel and taxi vouchers. The passengers were allowed 10 at a time on the aircraft after it was clear to retrieve there valuables/carryon’s. Maintenance checked out the aircraft and signed off on the log book as a good aircraft to fly. It is currently linked to flight 1207/DFW for MAY06.

column168: A driver pulled into a rest area to complete a routine haz mat load check and noticed an amount of spilled material coming under the rear door of the trailer.  The driver donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and spread an absorbent material onto the ground and placed absorbent pads onto the trailer floor.  He contacted his supervisor and also the local police and fire departments.  The response crew arrived, donned their appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the drum into a suitable salvage container.  The material used in the cleanup, as well as 1 shovelfull of dirt was also placed into the salvage drum.  The state of Oklahoma DEQ was notified of the incident but declined to issue an incident number.  The incident was handled by Tracy Verkler of Okla DEQ and also Wesley (who said they were not issuing a indident number.
column169: The load had not been adequately braced and blocked.  A drum shifted and dislodged the load lock, causing it to tip against another drum, popping the lid off of it and spilling.  The origin location was notified of the improper blocking and the driver was also instructed to inspect the load more carefully prior to transporting.

column168: The driver was using an electric pallet jack to move the IBC to the rear of the trailer so that a lift truck could remove the IBC from the trailer. The driver failed to stop the pallet jack before the front wheels traveled beyond the trailer's end plate. The downward angle of the pallet jack caused the IBC to slide off the pallet jack and fall to the building floor, bursting the top of the IBC. The release was captured within the containment area of the building. The liquid was subsequently vacuumed up and containerized for reuse.
column169: Drivers will receive additional training in the use of electric pallet jacks. Additionally, an apparatus will be placed at the rear of trailers to prevent the pallet jack and IBC from traveling beyond the rear opening of the trailer.

column168: A California PUC hazardous material inspector reported tank car SHPX 201528 with product on its side shell that was found during his inspection activities in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected SHPX 201528 finding the vacuum relief valve (VRV) 4 turns loose on its threaded connection. The responder removed the VRV, wiped then applied Teflon tape onto its threads and reapplied the VRV to a tool tight condition by 1245 hrs. PDT, 5/03/2011. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. The preponderance of the spillage on the tank shell and in the valve housing area had solidified as if it was from a previous spill. A small amount of fluid product around the base of the VRV was wiped. No ground impact from any spillage was observed.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF train was stopped on main track after a grade crossing collision with a highway vehicle. During the investigation phase of the crossing collision, the responding local F.D. observed an entrained tank car GATX 1607 dripping liquid from its bottom outlet valve (BOV). GATX 1607 was not impacted by the highway vehicle. GATX 1607 was carefully setout of the train on a nearby industry track with a catch receptacle placed under GATX 1607. After an inspection of GATX 1607 by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder; the responder reported that the BOV was slightly open and it was then closed. Also, the BOV's  closure cap's gasket was found to be deteriorated and it was replaced. The bottom outlet cap was then reapplied and tool tightened. Afterwards, the product drips ceased and no further product drips were observed. All product spillage evaporated and no ground impact from spillage was evident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Cargo shipment tendered and accepted on May 17, 2011 at 1615.  Nature of good declared: Food and Machine Parts, AWB # 027-80598965  During the acceptance procedure, the person tendering the shipment (George Hall) declared and signed through an electronic form that the shipment DID NOT contain any dangerous goods.  The shipment is made by 3 cardboard boxes at 192 lb of weight.  During the physical screening process:   Box 1: had a big metallic part of an unidentified machine and 6 bottles of growing plant enhancement (liquid).  Box 2: Poewr generator, used, with a gas tank that smelled of gasoline. Once the tank has been opened, gasoline was visible in the tank.  Box 3: Bucket with an unidentidied liquid that smelled like maple syrup.    At this point, I notified Alaska Cargo Help Desk, then I put a sign on the shipment: DO NOT LOAD.    Fabio Colasante
column169: My recommendation is to pay always extra attention during the screening process of cargo because undeclared dangerous goods can be potentially hiding (intentionally or not) in every shipment.

column168: Ward Trucking contacted ERTS to dispatch a contractor for clean up of a leaking drum in a trailer. The contractor over packed the leaking drum and cleaned up the impacted parking lot, adjacent soils and trailer floor. All material generated was containerized and transported for disposal.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling, the Hillis Transport vehicle was struck by a third party, which caused the trailer to dislodge from tractor and rollover into roadside ditch.  Trailer contained approximately 7,500 gallons of diesel fuel.  Hillis Transport dispatched a tanker to offload the damaged trailer, and recovered 3,000 gallons of diesel fuel during offload.  The remaining 4,500 gallons of diesel fuel were released to the soil within the roadside ditch.  The Pocahontas Fire Department responded to assess the site, along with the Arkansas Highway Department.  AR Highway Department utilized sand to create berms at both sides of contamination, in an effort to prevent migration.  Smith & Company of Poplar Bluff, Missouri was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Smith & Company used a vaccuum truck to recover the free liquid diesel fuel and water from the impacted ditch, and deployed sorbent boom and pads to secure the site.  Smith & Company worked at the direction of ARDEQ site representative Dean Vanderhoff, and returned on Monday, May 16th, to excavate the impacted soils, and restore site to preexisting condition.  Site was cleared per visual and olfactory observation, and microblaze solution was left on site as a precaution, to prevent residual contamination.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Hillis Transport LLC will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: Approximately 20 gallons of Sodium Hydroxide solution was released onto the trailer floor due to a forklift incident. The damaged drum was overpacked and granular absorbents were applied to the impacted floor. The waste was then containerized for disposal.

Driver was using his tractor product pump to unload. Driver used a 3" X 2" fitting  with a bleeder valve to reduce down for the customer's receiving line.  As the driver was unloading he discovered that the bleeder valve on the reducer mounted on the discharge side of the pump had vibrated open spilling the material.  Driver immediately closed the bleeder valve and shut down the product pump.  Driver inspected the fitting and found that the locking device on the ball valve was   not in place. driver reset the valve and secured it. driver completed the delivery.
column169: Upon his return to his terminal, the driver had the fitting inspected for defects.   I have instructed the driver to double check valves. And even though the may have a locking device, back that up with another securing device such as Velcro straps of tape.

column168: A van trailer was being unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility when a hissing sound was noticed.  The supervisor was notified along with the health and safety person.  Since the facility is outdoors, it was felt that the cylinder should be allowed to vent.  The cylinder was part of a household hazardous waste shipment.  IEMA was called and issued incident number H20110473.  When the cylinder completed venting, it was found that the valve had opened during the rigors of transportation.
column169: The origin location was notified and had a meeting with all persons involved in perpearing this shipment for transportation and reviewed propane cylinder handling protocol.  This was added to the preparation checklist for all future events.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT STATION TO DELIVER PRODUCT.  DRIVER HOOKED DP HIS HOSE TO THE TANKER FIRST AND THOUGHT HE HAD CONNECTED THE OTHER END OF THE HOSE TO THE DROP.  HE OPENED THE VALVE AND PRODUCT BEGAN TO FLOW FROM THE END OF THE HOSE.  DRIVER CLOSED VALVE AND STUCK THE FITTING ONTO THE DROP.  MSD WAS ONSITE AT THE TIME AND CALLED 911.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND JEFFERSON COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED ON SITE.  LEWIS TRANSPORT HAD CALLED GRA-KAT, AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE UNIT, AND THEY REPORTED TO THE SITE WITH A VAC TRUCK.  GRA-KAT DETERMINED THAT PRODUCT HAD GONE INTO 3 STORM DRAINS AND BEGAN TO SUCK PRODUCT FROM THOSE DRAINS.  THEY INTRODUCED WATER INTO THE DRAINS AND SUCKED THEM OUT AGAIN.  THEY CLEANED THE SURFACE OF THE STATION AND WERE GIVEN AN ALL-CLEAR BY THE KY EPA.  THE RECOVERED PRODUCT IS BEING TAKEN TO WASTE MANAGEMENT IN LOUISVILLE.  NRG WAS CALLED AS WELL AS KY EPA.
column169: LEWIS TRANSPORT, INC. HAS ALWAYS TRAINED THEIR DRIVERS TO HOOK TO THE FILL FIRST AND THEN THE TRUCK.  DRIVER ERROR IN PROCEDURE CAUSED SPILL OF PRODUCT.  LEWIS TRANSPORT, INC. WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN DRIVERS ON THE PROPER WAY TO DROP PRODUCT AND THIS WILL BE ADDRESSED IN FUTURE SAFETY MEETINGS.

column168: CN transportation department employee reported a vapor coming from the side of tank car UTLX 12205(L / HYDROCHLORIC ACID) during switching operations at the CN Decatur Yard, Decatur, IL. This employee reported being exposed to product vapors and requested medical treatment. The employee was transported at a local hospital and held overnight for observation. All appropriate departments were notified, tank car isolated in track. Local Fire Department Hazardous Materials Team responded noting a small hole in the right side of the tank shell. Fire Department Hazmat Team applied a patch to the hole which reduced the leak, product containment was placed under the car. CN's response team and the shipper's response contractor also responded and completed a tank car to tank car transfer of the product.  Residue product in UTLX 12205 neutralized, shipper to apply for OTMA to repair facility

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Tank car PROX 30070 was reported emanating a product odor in the railyard. Immediate inspection of PROX 30070 by a BNSF mechanical responder resulted in no liquid or vapor product release noted at that time, although a very slight product odor was present. PROX 30070 was cordoned off in the railyard. Re-inspection of PROX 30070 during daylight hours revealed a vapor hiss emanating from the pressure relief device (PRD) and product odor. A hazardous material response contractor was summoned and these responders confirmed that the 280.5 psig Midland PRD was the product odor and vapor source. The responders replaced the PRD seat and stem O-rings along with the O-ring retainer by 1305 hrs. PDT. 5/06/2011, thus eliminating any further product vapors and associated product odor. The seat O-ring appeared flattened with a groove along the entire circumference of the O-ring which would classify it as a 'compression set' caused failure.  Seal numbered 477340 was applied to the valve housing cover.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was en route from the shippers location to Clean Harbor’s in transit storage location in Bristol, CT for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities of hazardous waste for continuing transportation to the intended waste management facility. While transferring one container, it was discovered that approximately 6 ounces of material escaped from the bottom of the container. Facility personnel placed the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris from the van trailer. The container was secured and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility. All required local and state reports were made that included verbal reports to the Connecticut Department of Environmental Protection and local Fire Department.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a  thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to  either place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before transportation is initiated. In addition, the shipper was advised of the  incident and was requested to inspect all drums in current inventory for any containers with suspect integrity.

column168: The trailer was dolly downed for 10-day in-transit storage at the Baytown Transfer Facility prior to transportation to the Port Arthur Incineration Facility.  The trailer was undergoing routine inspection and container piece count when liquid material was observed on the floor of the trailer and on several wooden pallets.  All containers were removed from the trailer for visual inspection.     The spilled liquid was tested with pH paper and found to be a strong base. It was determined that one 275 gal plastic IBC tote containing caustic liquid was leaking from a seam along the bottom of the container.  It appears the weld seam had cracked and the liquid sloshing motion in the tote during transportation was enough to widen the crack to allow liquid to periodically drip out.    The contents of the leaking tote were transfered to a new clean empty tote.  All spilled liquid in the trailer and pallents adjacent to the leaking tote was cleaned using absorbent material.      No material was released to the environment.  All spilled material was contained within the transport vehicle.
column169: The container material had failed.  Our routine inspection program succesfully identified the leak prior to offering the load for additional transportation.    The incident will be communicated to the original offeror so that they can review their containers for physcal integrity prior to shipping in the future.

column168: On discovery of release emergency response personnel were contacted to site. Inspection of car showed Rupture Disc was burst and the top of Safety Vent Housing was missing. Rupture Disc replaced with 165psi Rupture disc and car secured for movement to consignee. Crushed lime stone was applied to a small 1 square foot area which indicated product had come in contact with ballas along side track.
column169: Car was evidently shipped with the Top of the Safety Vent Housing missing while it did not contribute to the release it still should have been on car before outbound movement and could have kept material from coming in contact with the ground. Reason for rupture disc being burst is not known since the car in question moved from a location in Mexico to consignee located in St. Louis Mo.

UTLX 202328 was noted by carrier personnel with product dripping from the bottom of the car.  Car isolated and shipper notified. column168: HOKX 111732 was noted by carrier personnel with product leaking from the top of the car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, React Environmental, responded and found the pressure relief device housing assembly bolts loose.  The top of the housing was removed and dried material was removed to allow a secure seal.  The housing was reassembled and the bolts properly tightened tool tight.    One employee was exposed to a small amount of material which splashed out during switching operations.  The employee showered and rinsed the exposed areas for 20 minutes per emergency action instructions.  There was some redness of the exposed skin.  No medical attention was sought.  No lost time.

column168: DURING THE MORNING DELIVERY CYCLE IN A RENTED VEHICLE, THE REAR CARGO DOOR OF THE VAN CAME OPEN AND SOME FREIGHT FELL OUT OF THE TRUCK. WHEN THE DRIVER FOUND OUT THE DOOR WAS OPENED HE PULLED OVER AND CORRECTED. PASSING MOTORIST FOUND SOME OVERNIGHT LETTERS AND TURNED IN AT A LOCAL FEDEX OFFICE. IT WAS LATER DISCOVERED THAT A RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL (IN A METAL DRUM) AND FALLEN OUT THE VEHICLE. THE HUSTON CONTACTS FOR OPERATIONS, SAFETY, SECURITY AND DANGEROUS GOODS WERE NOTIFIED TO ASSIST IN THE SEARCH AND INVESTIGATION. LATER THAT EVENING NOTIFICVAION WAS MADE TO THE STATE OF TEXAS REGARDING THE MISSING SHIPMENT (TX REPORT: I-8854). THE NRC WAS NOTIFIED THAT AA MOTORIST HAD FOUND THE DRUM AND TURNED IT INTO THE CLOSEST HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT STATION. FEDEX RETRIVED THE DRUM TOTALLY INTACT WITH NO DAMAGE AND SECURITY SEAL INTACT, AND DELIEVED IT TO DHL GLOBAL FORWARDINF (THE KNOWN RECIPIENT). FEDEX EXPRESS IS CONDUCTING INTERNAL INVESTIGATIONS AS TO THE CAUSE OF THE VEHICLE CARGO DOOR OPENING AND THE LOSS CARGO.

column168: Notified at 0844 hrs that DBUX 300307 out of Magellan appeared to be leaking product from the manway area.  Upon arrival it was observed that some product was bypassing the manway cover and gasket and running down the sides of the car. No product was observed on the ground.  Further investigation found that one manway bolt was misaligned and the others were barely tool tight allowing product to be released past the gasket. Magellan personell responded to the incident and checked the gasket, resealed the tank car and wiped down the product from the sides of the tank car. Scene was cleared at 1035 hrs.
column169: Magellan is investigating the incidents. They allege this could be a result of a bad torque wrench.

column168: UTLX 207433 was discovered leaking on 5092011 at approximately 0844 hrs by PTRA crews. The tank car was leaking from the manway account 5 of 8 dome bolts were loose. column168: Third car in 7 days leaking from the manway area out of Magellan Midstream account loose dome bolts. column169: Magellan continues to have issues with the dome bolts being properly tightened for transport. This is the third car that has leaked in 8 days. The cars were all released for transport on Fridays. Magellan is checking to see if this is a torque wrench issue of a loader issue.

column168: On 05/06/2011 at 1800 hrs., FRA Hazardous Material Inspector Roger Huff reported the following defects during inspection in Hawesville, KY, CSXT Skillman yard. CGTX 20698, a loaded tank car of Elevated Temperature Liquid N.O.S. (Coal Tar Pitch), leaking from the top of the rail car. The car was isolated in the rail yard and the shipper, Ruetgers Canada, Inc., was notified through CHEMTREC 2011-05-09-00075. Inspection found one loose man way bolt and the vapor line pipe was loose at the man way plate.The defects were communicated to shipper's representative, Alen McLeod 905-544-5519. On 05/12/2011 CSXT Hazmat Manager Jim Briski responded to secure the car, clean the spilled product and then released the tank car for transport to destination.        A switching move was performed for this incident.  A 7.1 QA Non conformance report will not be required for this incident.    Cause Code: 361  NARRI Severity Index: 5 (3+1+0) x (2+0) = 40

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, A TOTE OF LIQUID WAS FOUND LEAKING DUE TO THE VALVE WAS FOUND LOOSE.  PER SHIPPER'S RECOMMENDATION AND AUTHORIZATION.  THE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED AND THE TOTE WAS OKAYED AND FORWARDED ONTO CONSIGNEE.  A LINED SALVAGE DRUM, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED, WAS USED FOR THE CLEAN-UP AND AFFECTED MATERIALS.  THE DRUM IS BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: TOTES AND OTHER VARIOUS KINDS OF PACKAGINGS, CONTAINING CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE THOROUGHLY             INSPECTED BEFORE THEY LEAVE ORIGIN.  ALL TOTES MUST BE BLOCKED, BRACED, SECURED AND SHROUDED FOR ADEQUATE PROTECTION TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGING.  USE LOAD LOCK BARS, STRAPS AND MTY PALLETS TO ENSURE LOAD IS SAFE AND SECURE BEFORE MOVING.  PAILS, GABS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND/OR DUNNAGE.  USING DECK BARS OR LOAD LOCK BARS PROPERLY AND SAFELY TO LOAD FREIGHT ON TOP OF!  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS.  RETRAIN IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING, SIGNAGE STATING,  PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER TO MAKE SURE LIDS ON  DRUMS ARE SECURED.

column168: Cylinder was not in transport; it had previously been delivered to this location on May 16, 2011.  At approximately 4:00pm on May 31, 2011 plant personnel at Cleco/Lena plant noticed chlorine vapors leaking from a cylinder located near the water treatment plant.  Upon further inspection, they could smell chlorine. The cylinder appeared to be leaking toward the bottom of cylinder. All plant personnel were instructed by Cleco/Lena to shelter in place upstream. All personnel downstream of incident area were moved to area upwind. Contents of cylinder emptied in approximately 30 minutes. Chlorine was dispersed because of wind direction and speed. After inspection of cylinder, it was found to be a small hole approximately 3/8" in diameter.  Photos are available.
column169: C & L Aqua Pro is transporter of chlorine cylinders.  Altivia Corporation is the manufacturer/repackager and owner of the cylinders.  Altivia, the manufacturer/repackager of the cylinder will review inspection processes upon completion of the final investigation.  At this time cylinder is in shipment back to Altivia who can be reached at 713-658-9000.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 05/19/2011, while picking up railcars from the UP interchange track near MP 25.5 (Matteson Subdivision), Chicago Heights, IL, a CN transportation department employee reported an odor and vapor release from tank car TILX 261743 (L, Dicyclopentadine).   All appropriate departments notified. CN's response team responded, noting no signs of a vapor release. Safety relief devise monitored and no LEL levels recorded. All valves "snooped" with no indication of an active release noted. Tank car pressure noted at less than 5 psi. A slight odor was noted coming from the car's outer jacket, no LEL levels recorded, no leak noted. During a conference call with the shipper, it was decided to have a response contractor respond to the scene and inspect the car. Upon their arrival, no change was noted in the car, no leak found. Equipment released and moved to destination without further incident.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: TANK CAR WAS OVERFILLED TO SHELL FULL 1 PERCENT WAS REMOVED AND THE CAR WAS SECURED FOR TRANSPORTATION.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Car was reported to be leaking product from top of manway cover while moving.  Inspection of car revealed 8 of 8 manway swingbolts in position, not wrench tight.  Upon tightening 8 manway swingbolts, car was secured for transportation.   Car was reported to be leaking product from top of manway cover while moving. Inspection of car revealed 2 of 8 manway swingbolts in the down position, 6 of 8 manway swingbolts in position, not wrench tight. Upon tightening 8 manway swingbolts, car was secured for transportation.
column169: Conduct proper post inspection to ensure car is secure for transportation.

column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING UNLOAD.  THE CUSTOMER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND THE SPILL WAS RECOVERED TO A SALVAGE DRUM. column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS DELIVERED TO THE CUSTOMER WHO THEN CALLED BACK AND CLAIMED THAT WHAT SHE ORDERED WAS NOT INSIDE THE PACKAGE AND IT WAS LEAKING. THERE IS NO AIRBILL IN FILE.  THE CONSIGNMENT WAS DONE USING SHIPMANAGER.

column168: Driver arrived at this business (North American Composite) to deliver freight, when driver opened the rear door of truck he discovered liquid leaking on the floor and some dripping thru floor and onto ground. Driver called dispatch to report the leaking chemical and was instructed to call safety manager. Safety manager called 911 to start emergency response. Minnesota Duty officer was also called, report # 119010.  Emergency response evacuated business and sealed area, waited for spill response company, West Central Environmental. 1-888-544-9481.  WCEC response contained, neutralized and cleaned up spilled material. Leaking drum and spilled material recovered was transported back to shipper per their request.  During the cleanup process the cause of the leak was discovered, two nails were protruding thru the shippers pallet and wore a hole thru the platic drum bottom.  Shipper commanly ships mutiple containers shrink wrapped to their pallets.

column25: GREENFIELD LOGISTICS, LLC BY CAST TRANSPORTATION
column168: A rail flatcar (GFLX 147) with eight intermodal roll-off boxes riding atop was reported dripping an unknown liquid substance from one of these boxes.  GFLX 147 was carefully moved to the railyard's containment area (pit).  The shipper was notified and response contractors reported that two boxes BKRU 26209 and BKRU 26441 were observed dripping liquid at bottom box rust holes in these boxes. Interior inspection of these boxes revealed interior plastic liners applied surrounding dry and semi-dry material. Free liquid atop the material was noted in some of the eight boxes inspected and a drying agent was applied. No solid material was released from these eight roll-off boxes. Responders securely patched all rust holes with screwed in metal patches sealed by silicone sealant thus eliminating any further liquid dripping from BKRU 26209. All roll-off boxes removed from GFLX 147 were reloaded onto tractor trailers for over the road delivery to the consignee. Liquid spillage collected from BKRU 26209 was dried and placed back into the roll-off box. Liquid spillage in the containment area pit that mixed with standing water already in the pit was vacuumed and sampled for compounds of arsenic to determine appropriate disposal.

column168: LOADED TANKER WAS ON ENTRACE RAMP TO I-270 WEST AND DRIVER FAILE DTO CONTROL VEHICLE.  THE VEHICLE DEPARTED THE ROADWAY TO THE LEFT AND ROLLED OVER. UPON NOTIFICATION, , HOC TRANSPORT DISPATCHED THE OPERATIONS MANAGER TO THE SCENE WITH A TRUCK TO AFFECT AN OFF LOAD.  ALL DRIVDR RECORDS WERE SECURED BY THE SAFETY DIRECTOR.  THE OPERATIONS MANAGER SPOKE WITH THE REMEDIATION COMPANY WHO WAS ON SCENE (CALLED BY TOWING COMPANY)AND TOLD THEM NOT TO DO ANYTHING UNTIL HE ARRIVED. WHILE ONITS SIDE THE TANKER DISCHARGED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT (3-5 GALLONS) THROUGH THE EMERGENCY VENTING SYSTEM.  THE REMEDIATION COMPANY PLACED CONTAINMENT DEVICES TO GATHER THE SPILLAGE.  BEFORE THE OPERATIONS MANAGER COULD ARRIVE THE REMEDIATION COMPANY EMPLOYED VACCUUM TRUCHKS AND BEGAN PUMPING OUT COMPARTMENTS 1 &4 WIHTOUT CREATING AN AIR PRESSURE EQUALIZATION VENT/OPENING.  THE PUMPING ACTION DAMAGED O-RINGS IN COMPARTMENTS 1&4 AND INCREASED THE RATE OF DISCHARGE AND CAUSED ANOTHER ESTIMATED 15 GALLONS OF ETHANOL TO HIT THE GROUND.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED IN ACCORDANCE WITH REGULATIONS AND WAS WITNESSED BY AN ON-SITE EPA REPRESENTATIVE.  THE TRAILER WAS EVENTUALLY RIGHTED AND ALL PRODUCT PUMPED OFF . THE VEHICLE WAS THEN TOWED FROM THE SCENE. THE TOTAL ESTIMATED TIME FROM ROLLOVER TO RE-OPENING THE ENTRANCE RAMP WAS 7 HOURS.  CLARIFICATION: ITEMS 19 AND 31, QUANTITY RELEASED - 5 GALLONS BY ROLLOVER, 15 GALLONS BY HUMAN ERROR ON PART OF REMEDIATION COMPANY.  CLARIFICATION: ITEM 36, MAJOR ARTERY CLOSED - I-70 & I-270 WERE NEVER CLOSED. ONLY THE ENTRANCE RAMP TO I-270 WEST.
column169: HOC TRANSPORT AFTER INCIDENT ACTIONS: PUCO CONDUCTED AN ON-SITE FOCUSED INTERVENTION. NO RECORD KEEPING OR MANAGEMENT CONTROL VIOLATIONS. REVIEWER INDICATED DURING CLOSING CONFERENCE THAT THERE WERE NO COMPANY POLICY OR PROCEDURE FACTORS THAT CONTRIBUTED TO THIS ACCIDENT.  THERE WERE NO VIOLATIONS OR CITATIONS ISSUED AS A RESULT OF THIS INTERVIENTION.  COMPANY ACCIDENT INVESTIGATION PROCDEEDED IN ACCORDANCE WITH COMPANY POLICY. INCIDENT IS UNDER REVIEW BY OUR ACCIDENT COMMITTEE. CONSEQUENCES FOR THE DRIVER ARE PENDING MANAGEMENT AN DINSURANCE COMPANY DECISIONS.  SAFETY DIRECTOR HAS AMENDED THE JUNE 21 & 22 QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETING AGENDA TO INCLUDE DRIVER AWARENESS REFRESHER TRAINING ON SPEED MANAGEMENT AND ROLLOVER HAZARDS.  THE FACTS OF THIS INCIDENT WILL BE DISCUSSED DURING THESE SAFETY MEETINGS AS A "CASE STUDY" FOR OUR DRIVER FLEET SICUSSIONS WILL INCLUDE CAUSES, CONTRIBUTING FACTORS, DRIVING PRACTICES & HABITS AND PREVENTION OF FURTHER INCIDENTS.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: A 'natural gas' odor was reported in the railyard and all activity in the vicinity of the odor was ceased until the odor source was found and eliminated. The local gas energy service provider was called to investigate whether their gas pipelines were leaking; and no gas line leaks were found. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder and contract responders inspected railcars within the 'odor' zone. Responders reported finding tank car TEIX 33434 as the possible odor source. Further inspection of the valves and fittings under the valve housing cover revealed the base of the A-end liquid valve was frosted over and vapor hissing was audible emanating from this liquid valve's closure plug. The responders removed the frost from the valve's exterior for a detailed inspection. The valve was operated to its full closed position which reduced the audible vapor hiss. The liquid valve's closure plug was tool tightened 1/4 turn which eliminated the vapor hiss and associated odor. No liquid product release was observed. Securement response was concluded by 1310 hrs. PDT, 5/12/2011.

On 5/27/2011 at 2118 hrs., personnel at the CSXT Cumberland yard in Cumberland, MD,  discovered GATX 63213, a loaded tank car of Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, PPG Industries, local, state and federal agencies were notified. CHEMTREC report 2011-05-27-00270 issued. Specialized Professional Services, Inc. (SPSI), a CSXT emergency response contractor was dispatched to the scene and found the rupture disk on the non re-closing pressure relief device had deployed. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Denise Gil 304-266-8292. SPSI personnel replaced the rupture disk with a like in kind and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.    This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 441  NARRI: 2 (3+5+0) x (2+0) = 32

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: Driver, was at the service unit to dropping off a load.   Driver connected to the liquid line, but did not connect to the vapor line and when he unloaded the product this caused the vapor pressure to go up to 215 which resulted in blowing swage nipple on the pump to blow out.  Releasing a liquid leak.    Driver shut down everything immediately and reported this to Local Management who responded right away.  The release continued - water was put on the release and some of the propane was pumped out of the tank to lower the pressure.      The Fire Department was notified but did not respond.   Once they got the pressure to start dropping, they drained the piping to stop the leak.  They took the piping apart to fix the leak. Unable to complete repair as they had to order a new swage nipple.    No nearby drains or waterways.
column169: Repairs have been made.  All proper precautions were taken after the incident.  Employees who fail to follow our policies are often times required to write and present a safety meeting to their peers covering the infraction they committed.

SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED BY THE SHIPPER ABOUT 1:17 P TODAY. HE TOLD THE AGENT IT WAS "WATER TEST EQUIPMENT" AND SIGNED THAT THIS SHIPMENT DOES NOT CONTAIN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WE ARE DOING NEW CARGO AGENT TRAINING, SO A PHYSICAL SEARCH WAS DONE ON THIS SHIPMENT. SHE FOUND NUMEROUS HAZARDOUS ITEMS IN THE BOX AND ASKED IF ANY OF THIS WAS OK OR NOT. SHE DIDN'T THINK SO. ANOTHER AGENT LOOKED UP SOME OF THE ITEMS ONLINE AND A DIFFERENT AGENT LOOKED UP SOME OF THE UN NUMBERS AND IT WAS DECIDED THERE SHOULD POSSIBLY HAVE BEEN A SHIPPERS DECLARATION, LIMITED QUANTITY INFORMATION OR POSSIBLY AN EXCEPTION FROM DOT (WHICH NONE WASN'T GIVEN). WE CALLED THE TEST KIT COMPANY HACH COMPANY AND ASKED FOR THE MSDS AND ANY INFORMATION ON THE "TEST KIT" ITEMS. THE REGULAR SHIPPERS HAD GONE HOME, BUT THEY SENT THE MSDS SHEETS. WE TRIED CALLING JEFF DIETZ (LOCAL FAA PERSON), BUT HE IS OUT OF TOWN, SO WE LEFT HIM A MESSAGE. ANOTHER AGENT AND I LOOKED FOR THE REPORTING FORM, BUT SINCE THERE ARE MULTIPLE HAZARDOUS ITEMS, WE WERE TO DO A "PAPER FORM" BUT COULDN'T FIND ONE EARLIER. WE PUT THE SHIPMENT ON HOLD, ADVISED THE SHIPPER AND IT IS LOCATED IN THE BACK ROOM ON THE LEAD DESK. I SENT AN EMAIL TO OUR MANAGER, AND HE ASKED ME TO CALL THE NORTHWEST MOUNTAIN REGION AFTER HOURS NUMBER AND ASK FOR SOMEONE TO CALL ME BACK. SHE WAS ABLE TO TRANSFER ME. I TALKED TO SKY LANDIS. HE ASKED ME TO REPORT IT AND EMAIL HIM PICTURES, ETC. AND HE WILL HAVE SOMEONE FROM SEATTLE CALL ME TOMORROW.    *CORROSIVE SOLID, ACIDIC, INORGANIC, NOS UN3260 CLASS 8 PACKING GROUP III 200 COUNT   SULFAMIC ACID UN2967 CLASS 8 PACKING GROUP III 500 G   ZINC POWDER UN1436 CLASS 4.3 PACKING GROUP III 200 COUNT

column168: Tank car TILX 320125 was reported emanating a product odor in the railyard. BNSF responders inspected TILX 320125 finding the liquid line ball valve was the odor source. This angle valve was not fully closed and its closure plug was missing. Responders closed the liquid valve and product odor dissipated. No liquid product release was observed at the liquid valve.    Also, the responders found the bottom operated bottom outlet valve's (BOV) closure cap (BOC) was not applied and hanging from its retention chain. The BOC was applied and tool tightened. The BOV operating handle was not pinned securely and it was properly pinned in the closed position. No product release was observed from the closed BOV.

column14: CONSTR ZONE US 22 AT BAKERS RI
column168: OUR DRIVER PULLED UP WITHIN ABOUT THREE CAR LENGHTS OF A STOPPED PASSENGER VEHICLE IN A CONSTRUCTION ZONE WITH A FLAGGER AND CAME TO A STOP. HE SAW A FUEL HAULER APPROACHING BEHIND HIM, BUT HIS MAIN ATTENTION WAS ON THE FLAGGER AND THE CONSTRUCTION AREA AHEAD. SUDDENLY HE WAS STRUCK HARD FROM BEHIND. OUR DRIVER WAS BOUNCED AROUND IN HIS CAB. HIS DRIVER SEAT BROKE AND HE FOUND HIMSELF LYING IN THE SLEEPER BERTH WITH HIS SEAT BELT ACROSS HIS LEGS WHEN HIS VEHICLE STOPPED MOVING.    THIS VIOLENT REAR-END COLLISION RESULTED IN SIGNIFICANT DAMAGE TO OUR TRAILER (CONSIDERED A TOTAL LOSS BY ZURICH, NA INSURANCE COMPANY). THE FORCE OF THE COLLISION SHOVED OUR TRACTOR-TRAILER FORWARD INTO THE REAR OF THE PASSENGER VEHICLE AHEAD. THE FUEL HAULER WHO REAR-ENDED US WAS LIFE-FLIGHTED TO THE HOSPITAL, AND THEN RELEASED THE NEXT DAY. OUR DRIVER AND THE PASSENGER VEHICLE DRIVER WERE TRANSPORTED BY AMBULANCE TO A HOSPITAL EMERGENCY ROOM. OUR DIRVER WAS RELEASED LATER THE SAME AFTERNOON AFTER EVALUATION AND TREATMENT (WHIPLASH). ALL INJURIES WERE CAUSED BY THE FORCES OF THE COLLISION.    DAMAGE TO THE CARGO TANK TRAILER WAS ALSO CAUSED BY THE FORCE OF THE COLLSION FROM BEHIND. WITNESSES SAID THE FUEL HAULER DID NOT EVEN APPLY HIS BRAKES AS HE APPROACHED THE VEHICLES STOPPED AT THE CONSTRUCTION ZONE DESPITE OVER 1000 FEET OF CLEAR VIEW OF THE STOPPED TRAFFIC (PER HIGHWAY PATROL ON THE NEWS COVERAGE) AND SIGNS WARNING OF A "FLAGGER AHEAD." THE FORCE OF THE COLLISION RIPPED THE DELIVERY PIPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CARGO TANK. THIS LEFT A HOLE ABOUT 4" ACROSS AT THE BOTTOM OF THE CARGO TANK. THE TANK WAS EMPTY, BUT A SMALL AMOUNT OF RESIDUE FROM THE LAST LOAD REMAINED IN THE TANK (POSSIBLY A GALLON). IT WAS THROWN FORWARD WHEN THE REAR OF THE CARGO TANK WAS HIT AND (ACCORDING TO SOME WITNESSES TOSSED ABOUT 20 FEET INTO THE AIR) AND REMAINED THERE SINCE THE REAR OF THE TRAILER REMAINED ELEVATED EVEN AFTER THE VEHICLES WERE SEPARATED. SOME VAPOR FROM THE RESIDUAL ACID CAME OUT OF THE HOLE BEFORE IT WAS TEMPORARILY PATCHED BY THE EMERGENCY RESPONDERS (ADJACENT TO HARRISON COUNTY WHERE THE COLLISION OCCURRED), TOLD ME THAT ANY ACID THAT MIGHT DRIPPED FROM THE HOLE WAS "VERY MINIMAL." THE OHIO EPA REPRESENTATIVE ON THE SCENE AGREED THAT THERE WAS ESSENTIALLY NO RELEASE OF LIQUID ACID, JUST THE VAPOR. I UNDERSTAND EMERGENCY RESPONDERS PATCHED THE TANK AND THEN A CLEAN-UP CREW, INCIDENT MANAGEMENT SPECIALIST OF CADIZ, OH (AFFILIATED WITH WESTFALL TOWING), ABSORBED AND CLEANED UP THE LONG TRAIL OF FLUIDS THAT WERE EJECTED FROM THE ENGINE COMPARTMENT OF THE TRACTOR WHICH HIT US (APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS THAT MAY HAVE CONTAINED ENGINE COOLAND, OIL, WASHER FLUID, TRANSMISSION FLUID, DIESEL FUEL, POWER STEERING FLUID, ETC.)    ONCE WE WERE GIVEN ACCESS TO THE CARGO TANK AT THE IMPOUND LOT, OUR MECHANICS GEARED UP AND NEUTRALIZED THE REMAINING ACID SOLUTION IN THE FRONT OF THE CARGO TANK WITH SODA ASH. THEN THEY MADE A MORE SECURE PATCH OF THE HOLE IN PREPARATION FOR THE TRAILER
column169: IT PROBABLY IS NOT PRACTICABLE TO BUILD A VEHICLE TO TAKE A FULL-FORCE COLLISION FROM BEHIND WHILE STOPPED AND NOT SUSTAIN SIGNIFICANT DAMAGE. AT SOME POINT THE EXTRA WEIGHT OF THE REINFORCEMENT WOULD SEVERELY LIMIT THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WEIGHT THAT COULD BE LEGALLY CARRIED. I DO NOT KNOW THE REASON WHY THE FUEL HAULER FAILED TO STOP OR EVEN SLOW DOWN, BUT I HAVE CONFIDENCE LAW ENFORCEMENT WILL THOROUGHLY INVESTIGATE THIS EVEN TO DETERMINE THE UNDERLYING CAUSE OF THE COLLISION AND TAKE SUITABLE ACTION.

column168: A BNSF switch job was pulling rail cars from a bowl track in the railyard and during this movement derailed five rail cars including tank car TILX 110483. The cause of this derailment was attributed to a gapped switch point and irregular cross-level of track at point of derailment. TILX 110483 derailed on its side and struck other rail cars standing on an adjacent track when derailing. This impact at the top valve housing cover area resulted in a compromise at TILX 110483's pressure plate releasing product. TILX 110483 was uprighted at 0105 hrs. PDT, 5/16/2011 which ended any further product release. Air monitoring was initiated and continued throughout this incident. The remaining lading within TILX 110483 was transferred to another suitable tank car on 5/16/2011 without further incident. Ground spillage was neutralized in place. All impacted soils were then excavated and stockpiled with additional neutralizing agents mixed into the stockpile to achieve acceptable levels on the pH scale.

column168: Air contained within an underground pipeline was forced to the highest end of the pipeline when two tracks with a total of 36 cars were opened and flooded the pipeline. When the car at the highest point was opened, the air pressure inside the pipeline was greater than the weight of the ethanol in the car and the car when opened at the belly valve, acted like a relief point for the air. The mass of air bubbles caused the ethanol to spill form the open manway on top of the car.
column169: Site specific proecedures for offloading have been revised to reflect what order the railcars shall be opened when offloading to prevent the trapping of the air pocket.     Terminal management has also contacted a vendor to review the system so a pressure relief valve can be installed.

column168: During the loading of Trimac trailer 496059 the atmospheric pressure relief valve opened when the trailer pressure exceeded the set point.  The loading sequence was stopped immediately and the relief valve closed after 4.65 pounds of VOC was vented to the atmosphere.   Our investigation with Trimac has revealed that there were two mechanical failures and a loader oversight.  A Trimac power unit air line leak to the vapor recovery valve caused the valve to close allowing pressure to increase in the trailer.  Additionally, the ExxonMobil vapor recovery line low flow cut-out switch failed to operate and shut down the loading when the vapor recover valve closed and pressure starting building in the trailer.  Finally, the loader failed to follow the loading checklist and shut down the loading operation when the pressure increased above 20 psig.
column169: Trimac and ExxonMobil will continue to follow our inspection and preventative maintenance programs to minimize the potential for future defects.  ExxonMobil has decided to evaluate the current frequency of inspection and PM for the low flow cut-out switch for potential changes.  ExxonMobil will re-enforce loader expectations of using the loaders checklist and ensuring all trailers remain below 20 psig during the loading.

column169: PROPER PACKAGING, USE DUNNAGE, DECK BARS AND AIR BAGS TO PROPERLY BLOCK AND BRACE FOR SAFELY TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  PLACE DUNNAGE UNDER DRUMS, BAGS, PAILS AND TOTES TO PREVENT SHARP OR POINTED OBJECTS FROM PUNCTURING THE BOTTOM. column168: SR 347 is a 4 lane divided hwy. There were two north bound vehicles #1 & #2 and our Tank Truck #3 was south bound. The leading north bound vehicle #1 was pulling a little utility trailer. He decided to make a U-turn across the median area. The #2 vehicle hit #1.  The trailer broke loose and rolled over scattering materals across the north bound lanes. Vehicle #2 went to the right shoulder and rolled over. Vehicle #1 Catapulted across the median and crashed into the left side of our trailer ending at the traier tandems. The force of impact broke the trailer tandums and subframe from the rear of the tank.  A crack about 2 feet long 1/2 inch wide appeared and Diesel fuel leaked out onto the shoulder of the roadway. The Fire Department arrived within 15 minutes minutes and used a putty to slow the leak, but the majority of the product had leaked out.  A pump Truck arrived within the hour and the balance of the load was transfered.

column168: Entrained tank car TCIX 21139 parked in a siding track was observed emanating a small vapor plume at the A-end of this tank car as reported by a passing BNSF train. Responders were able to plug a small corrosion hole in the A-end upper tank head stopping product release by 2140 hrs. CDT, 5/26/2011. An interior liner failure was suspected. TCIX 21139 was separated from the train to isolate it for product transfer and during this movement the plug dislodged but was resecured by 2300 hrs. CDT, 5/26/2011. TCIX 21139 was monitored by responders until the product transfer into another suitable tank car was completed without further incident by 1000 hrs. CDT, 5/27/2011. Spillage on TCIX 21139 was neutralized and cleaned by 1104 hrs. CDT, 5/27/2011. All observed ground spillage was neutralized with applications of soda ash.  FRA-11050367 movement approval was received to move TCIX 21139 to a BNSF railyard for furtherance.     The side specification stencil on TCIX 21139 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2006 and the rubber lining applied 10/2006.

column162: SENIOR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND COMPLIANCE
column168: KCS responder arrived Port Arthur yard (7:40pm) shortly after shipper Total Petro Chemical responder. The shipper found lading leaking from the liquid induction line closure cap. Slight internal tank car pressure from afternoon temperature expansion caused lading to push out past the defective closure. Appears tank car was offered with pipe cap closure not properly prepared with teflon tape and tool tight. The shipper responder thought cause may have been worn cap threads and applied a new closure cap with teflon tape correcting the release. Photo inspection of the old closure cap threads appear that device should have functioned correctly. The release is estimated at 4 gallons. The shipper neutralized the released Sulfuric acid. Shipper responder was Charles Kosh, 409-985-0237.     KCS emergency services were activated to provide for railroad safety qualified services to mitigate this emergency (e.g., special switching for safety isolation, yard service interruption, Critical Incident Desk notifications, emergency response, management oversight, train/yard crew delay, and regulatory notification reports).  KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 may apply.    Note,  Item 27, amount in package, was estimated by f5800.1 report preparer. This action was required to facilitate data acceptance by defective PHMSA DOT IT system edits. Specifically, this estimated quantity was required for two reasons:   (1)because the shipper only provided bulk quantity on shipping paper, as 1 Tank Car, per PHMSA DOT requirements; and   (2)because the PHMSA DOT e-system requires data in this field which match the same units of measure as found in the capacity field.   KCS will continue to report in this fashion unit instructed differently by DOT or PHMSA.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  Also, please reference http://nar.aar.com/ for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: PGTX 400252 was reported leaking from the protective housing area at 2215 hrs on May 27, 2011 at the PTRA North Yard. The shipper, Stolt Terminals, was contacted and they stated that they would not have anyone avialable to respond to the incident until Tuesday, May 31, due to the holiday weekend. PTRA notified M&M Protection. Emergency response personell from M&M Protection responded to the incidents. Investigation found that the one of two one inch air lines on the car was leaking from the packing gland on the 90 degree ball valve. Both one inch lines had loose packing glands and valve handles.  M&M tightened the packing gland nut and stopped the leak at 0030 hrs on May 28, 2011.  The car was washed with a solution to neutralize the corrosive material on the car and the ground. M&M also neutralized product on the ground where the car was initially located before the leak was observed during switching moves. Total product released is estimated at three to four gallons. The scene was cleared at 0310 hrs.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling on Route 11, in Wallagrass, Maine, the cargo tank truck was involved in a vehicle accident, which caused the truck to rollover, and  damaged the compartments of the trailer.  The Maine Department of Environmental Protection responded to assess the site, along with the Aroostook County Emergency Services.  Maine DEP assisted in pumping off the remaining liquid within the damaged tank(s), and recovered 3,200 gallons of virgin gasoline into a rescue tanker provided by JJ Noble Trucking.  Approximately 5,000 gallons of gasoline were released to the loose bedrock area atop the ledge where the incident occurred.  Due to the location of the incident, a site survey was conducted, and MEDEP brought in a hydrogeologist and engineer to perform site sampling, and determine impact.  Maine DEP will coordinate ongonig site response and remedial activities until site is deemed for closure.  There were no injuries or exposures reported as a result of the release.
column169: The release was accidental, and occurred due to a vehicle accident.  JJ Noble Trucking will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: AT THE REQUEST OF MR. DANNY MCCOURT, RAILROAD SAFETY INSPECTOR, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL, USDOT, FRA, THIS DOT F5800.1 WAS SUBMITTED.  CHEMSOLV NOTES THE SIDOIUM BISULFATE IS A PACKING GROUP III, CLASS 8 IAW SECTION. 171.16(D).                                                       23 MAY 2011 AT 07:00 BEGAN TRANSLOADING FROM RAILCAR GATX 63922 TO A TANKER.  TOP-LOADING FITTING WAS NOT AVAILABLE, WENT TO BOTTOM FITTING ON RAILCAR.  UNSCREWED 2" PLUG, WHEN PRODUCT BEGAN TO DISCHARGE.  PERSONNEL CONTACTED MANAGEMENT AT 07:30 TO INFORM THEM OF THE SITUATION.  PERSONNEL DONNED ADDITIONAL PPE AND REPLACED PLUG.  AN ESTIMATED 55 - 275 GALLONS OF SODIUM BISULFITE 40% DISCHARGED TO THE PARKING LOT AND CONTAINMENT.  MANAGEMENT DETERMINED THAT THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY WAS        NOT EXCEEDED, NOR WERE ANY OF THE CRITERIA MET IN SECTION 171.15.  THEREFORE, THE NRC WAS NOT CONTACTED.  CORPORATE CONTACTED THEIR SPILL CONTRACTOR, WHO RESPONDED AT 08:49 TO REMEDIATE THE RELEASE.  THE CONTRACTOR VACUUMED THE MIX OF SODIUM BISULFITE AND RAINWATER FROM THE PARKING LOT AND CONTAINMENT AREA FOR DISPOSAL.  THE AREA WAS FINE-CLEANED, UTILIZING STAY-DRY.  THE ACCIDENT INVESTIGATION CONCLUDED WHEN  THE 2" PLUG WAS REMOVED AND THE INTERNAL WAS APPARENTLY STUCK IN THE OPEN POSITION; ALTHOUGH THE VALVE WAS LOCKED AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT.
column169: Chemsolv modified their operating procedure for top unloading corrosive railcars.

Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was unloading at a customer location. The driver was new to the delivery site and it had no address listed on the site. After speaking with the customer and dispatch the driver felt as though he was at the correct location and began to unload ULSD. While unloading a customer truck came in and informed the driver he was in fact at the wrong location. The driver had unloaded 4200 gallons that would be pumped back onto the truck and delivered next door at the correct location. The Terminal Manager arrived to assist in this and was on the top of the truck ensuring the load would fit, but as it was getting close to full, the product bubbled slighly and leaked out of the top of the trailer tank. The pump was immediately shut off but approximately 10-15 gallons leaked onto the concrete and then was covered with sand. SWS First Response came to the scene to haul away the sand. The product never reached soil or drains.
column169: The terminal manager allowed for the load to come to close to the max capacity for the compartment.

column168: A company owned cargo loaded in Geismar, La. was transporting a load of Formaldehyde Solution westbound on I-10.  The Martin Transport driver experienced a tire failure and pulled over to the shoulder to inspect.  Once on the shoulder, a small drip was detected under the trailer.  The driver called Martin Transport and reported the drip and the tire.  Martin Transport reported the incident to La State Police.   On close inspection, it was determined that a shell repair performed several years ago had failed and a pinhole opening had formed at a repair weld.  When traveling down the road, product would slosh up and out of the pinhole opening.  However, if the trailer was sitting still, no leak was detected.  The product was transferred into another Martin Transport trailer and delivered to the customer.  The trailer was cleaned and purged of all product and delivered to Geo's Tank Service for repairs.   It should be noted that since this tank was originally repaired, it has always passed it's yearly specification inspections.
column169: Continue to operate quality equipment and continue to perform yearly federal and state inspections, as per regulations.

column168: Tank car PTRX 7015 was involved in a derailment and experienced a puncture and large tear to the B-end head of the tank car.  The damage penetrated both the outer tank and the inner tank.  Further, there was a large crushed/torn area on the upper A-end of the car.  The damage to the car released the contents of the car which ignited in the course of the derailment and were completely consumed.  Tank car PTRX 7017 was involved in a derailment and experienced a large amount of damage to the lower B left side, penetrating both the outer tank and the inner tank.  The damage to the car released the contents of the car which ignited in the course of the derailment.  After several hours of fire involvement, an explosive charge was used to create a vent hole to assist in allowing the product to flow from the tank, expediting removal and consumption of the product.  Following the detonation of the charge, all of the product was consumed by fire and the car was then moved to be salvaged at a later time.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 05/03/2011 Executive Jet Management, Inc. 4556 Airport Road Cincinnati OH 45226 offered for shipment on State-Wide Delivery Service, LLC a package containing three aircraft fire bottle squibs, described in items 14, 15 and 16 on page 1 of this report.  The shipment was not packaged, marked or declared as required by 49 CFR Parts 171-180 of the Hazardous Materials Regulations.  There was no release or damaged to persons or property due to this shipment.  Executive Jet Management became aware of the undeclared shipment on or about 05/31/2011. The Executive Jet Management Director of Safety conducted a formal investigation and determined that the shipment should have been packaged, marked and declared in accordance with the Hazardous Material Regulation.  The person offering the shipment, a Executive Jet Management employee, was trained as a Hazardous Materials Shipper in accordance with 49 CFR 172.700.  The shipment packing slip automatically noted that the items were hazardous materials but the person offering the shipment believed the shipment was not declarable because it was being transfer inter-company.
column169: All Executive Jet Management authorized hazardous materials shippers have been briefed on this incident and are scheduled to received additional training on their responsibilities as authorized hazardous material shippers for the company.  Directly related to this incident those authorized to ship hazardous materials on behalf of Executive Jet Management have been informed that any shipment, even inter-company that is transported by air, sea or land if classified as hazardous materials must be packaged, marked and declared as required by the Hazardous Materials Regulations.  State-Wide Delivery Service was notified by phone of the undeclared shipment on or about 06/01/2011.

column168: On May 28, 2011 at approximately 8:30am, a company driver had just completed loading at COG Operating - Beverly Lease (oil well site) on County Road 25 (gravel) East of Crane, Texas.  While proceeding on County Road 25, the driver took his attention off the road for a moment and allowed his front steer tire and duals to fall off the improved roadway onto the soft shoulder.  The driver immediately responded to the situation and attempted to bring the transport back on top of the roadway.  In doing so, the driver over-corrected his steering.  This inappropriate reaction caused the weight of the load to carry the tractor-trailer over on its right side.  The tractor trailer came to rest in the bar ditch on the north side of the road.  The drive exited the cab and immediately notified his supervisor.  Crane County Sheriff's Department responded to the scene.  TXDPS declined to respond.  Company personnel responded to the scene and expedited a response to include:  Load transfer to another truck, uprighting the damaged transport, and cleaning up the affected area.  Approximately 10-15 gallons of crude oil were released from the cargo tank due to a damaged rubber sleeve connecting the cargo tank vent valve to the vent line.  The spilled crude oil was recovered and removed from the site.
column169: The root cause of this lay-over accident was due to the driver's inappropriate reaction to the situation of dropping the tires off the improved roadway.  Contributing factors also include multi-tasking while driving and inattention to surroundings.  The vehicle's estimated speed just before the lay-over was 15 mph.  The driver had enought time and sufficient shoulder to respond appropriately.  The driver should have maintained his direction of travel, and slowly applied the brakes until he came to rest.  He could have then easily returned the transport back onto the improved roadway.  Additional awareness training on the factors that caused and contributed to this event is warranted.  All company drivers will participate in an accident review process to include discussion on the hazards associated with multi-tasking, the importance of paying attention to surroundings, and the proper response to this type of driving scenario.

column168: During the morning hours,at approximately 11:00 AM, we (Atlantic  Coastal Fuels) were at the Port of Palm Beach, Gulfstream Heavylift facility, filling a petroleum trailer  to be exported to the Bahamas. The fuel was being transferred via pump-off procedures to the receiving trailer. The trailer  had (5) individual tank compartments,each of which had a gate valve for ingress and egress of fuel. The transfer of fuels was being completed by (2) (ACF) personnel. Upon completion of the  3rd  compartment from the rear the employee, Aneel Singh proceeded to close the gate valve prior to disconnecting the transfer hose and moving to compartment (4). The gate valve was turned down to a stopping point indicating it was  closed. But upon disconnection it was immediately apparent that the valve had not fully closed. The employee promptly dealt with the situation and wrestled the valve closed by opening it slightly and forcing it past the sticking point in the valve thus ending the flow of fuel.  The resulting spill was approximately (25) gallons of Jet Fuel. Gulfstream Heavylift  was immediately notified and they contacted the Fire Department. The spill was contained and on asphalt. At no point did any fuel reach any natural resources or do any damage to the environment. The fueling operation  ceased and the trailer  was secured.  (ACF) called our emergency response company,Cliff Berry, and had them immediately respond to the incident. The estimated release was (25) gallons. I have copied you on the non-hazardous waste manifest  from Cliff Berry but will summarize here for you. The result of the cleanup, combined with the water sprayed by the fire department is as follows:    600 Lbs. of (Used oil Dry)  70 Gallons of (Non-processable solids/sludge from wastestream)  700 Gallons of (oily water for re-cycle)      We were advised that no further action was required in light of the fact the situation was handled by the Port and it's response personnel. Mainly in part due to the small size of the spill. The ruling from the fire department and the Port Director  was that the trailer  that caused the incident would no longer be permitted in the Port going forward. The trailer was returned to the Bahamas and will not be returned to the states again.  The direct cause of the incident was a faulty gate valve on the trailer. The trailer  was manufactured previous to 1980 and all systems on it were old and in various stages of dis-repair. The release of fuel was less than a minute and the valve was forced closed. Immediately upon release the employees of (ACF) began to contain the spill with pads and pigs. Cliff Berry advised us that the spill did not exceed 25 gallons and was well contained. The expense of cleanup would have further been reduced had the fire department not watered down the situation which spread it further. I have also copied you on the Cliff Berry billing to show the breakdown of services and charges.  I,Charles Eldon,owner of Atlantic Coastal Fuels,
column169: In light of the situation that occurred, first and foremost the trailer in question is not permitted in the Port for further transport of fuel. More importantly, all future transfers will and are being performed by either myself or my immediate senior supervisor. We are thoroughly checking the units to be filled prior to any transfer operations. Also taking precautionary measures during as well as at the end of loading procedures to insure all components are secured and closed prior to any disconnections being made. Going forward the trailers will be phased out and be replaced by more reliable ISO containers as per agreement with Port of Palm Beach Director. The equipment that failed is owned and maintained by a offshore entity. We already have one (ISO) unit in operation and are acquiring more to facilitate the needs of this customer.  Atlantic Coastal Fuels strives to maintain the utmost in safety and is thorough in procedures regarding hazardous materials. All the necessary changes have been made to insure this type of incident does not have a re-occurrence. It is the only incident resulting in spillage in the history of our existence,and with vigilance will be the last.

column168: Passenger Allen did not declare his Liquid Oxygen tank to any Airline agent.  He did declare it to the TSA at the Security checkpoint.  The TSA examined it but did not ask for a Doctor's prescription.  The passenger advised that it was for medical use for himself and the TSA allowed him to continue with it to the gate.  Again, Passenger Allen did not declare his Liquid Oxygen tank to the gate agent.    Once boarded and the aircraft was in the process of taxiing for takeoff/on takeoff roll, a Flight Attendant noticed the passenger was doing things with his carry-on stowed under the seat in front of him.  Shortly after takeoff, the Flight Attendant investigated and discovered the passenger had a canula around his neck and attached to his nose.  The passenger did not seem to realize that he was doing anything wrong.  By the original quick inspection of the device, the Flight Attendant determined that maybe it was a Portable Oxygen Concentrator (POC).  However, she questioned why she had not been informed by ground personnel that the device was on-board per company procedure.  A second Flight Attendant became involved.  Her inspection revealed that the device was developing frost on the outside of the container and then she discovered the small Class 5.1, Oxidizer and Class 2.2, Non-Flammable Gas labels on the canister.  The passenger was immediately directed by the Flight Attendant to turn off/close the valve on the device.  The Captain was informed and made the decision to divert back to the Norfolk Airport because indications were that the canister contained Liquid Oxygen which is forbidden on passenger aircraft.    Upon arrival at the gate, local authorities met the flight.  The passenger and the Liquid Oxygen canister were removed from the aircraft and the flight redeparted.      There was no release other than the gaseous oxygen that the passenger inhaled during the brief duration of the flight.
column169: Mr. Allen was a non-revenue passenger.  He is the son of an employee and has sickle cell anemia.  He had recently began using oxygen of his own choosing when he walks long distances and becomes exhausted.  The employee is his mother and was not awar that her son had begun using oxygen.      Procedures are being changed to improve automated e-mail communications to non-revenue passengers to ensure when they are booked that they understand the dangers associated with carrying prohibited or forbidden hazardous materials.  In addition, the Trip Book that applies to all employees and their authorized travellers is being ammended again to specifically include Liquid Oxygen as an item that cannot be carried.    Have the manufacturers of Liquid Oxygen carriers for medical use been required to place a label on their products that specifically states they are forbidden for carriage and use on board a passenger aircraft when they contain Liquid Oxygen?

column168: Upon loading Flight 55 to Prudhoe Bay, on Friday May 27th, it was noticed that a cargo shipment containingconsumer commodity ORM-D was disintegrating and emitting vapors. Agent Vogel informed his lead of a possibleleak and the box was removed. The lead taped the box as to try to keep it intact. This shipment originated inAnchorage on Flight 55 on the 26th of May, was bumped in Fairbanks due to weather. The box upon discovery wasintact but continued to disintegrated during the morning. It appears to be a leaking or faulty cap on one of the 12bottles in the box. The amount released we estimate it to be approximately 2oz of the 32oz in the container. Spillhas been reported to TGI Freight Anchorage (shippers), Alaska Airlines Environmental Affairs and Dangerous Goods Management.

column168: PACKAGE WAS FOUND ON THE SORT AISLE WHERE IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A CORNER OF THE BOX WAS WET.. PACKAGE WAS TRANSPORTEDWAS TIGHT BUT THE PRODUCT WAS LEAKING OUT ANYWAY .
column169: CHECK CLOSURE FOR LEAKAGE.

column168: The package was unloaded with leakage noted on the box.  Examination of the inner container revealed that the container(s) had loose cap(s) and leaked.  The leakage was contained.  The cap(s) were secured.  The carton was wet but otherwise undamaged.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.
